[1] Snow mould - USA: (Northwest)
Date: Thu 5 May 2011
Source: Capital Press [edited]
http://www.capitalpress.com/content/dw-winter-kill-w-art-050611


Snow mold ravages fields
------------------------
Now that most of the snow has melted from Northwest fields, poor,
withered winter wheat stands have shown up in several areas around the
region. The damage is the likely result of snow mold, said Juliet
Marshall, University of Idaho.

The snow mold fungus thrives under an insulating cover of snow. In
some areas, snow fell on unfrozen ground in November [2010] and stayed
for months, providing the perfect breeding ground for the disease to
develop, she said. "The longer that snow cover is there, the more
opportunity for the fungus to take advantage of the weakened plant."

100 days of continuous snow cover is enough for snow mold to develop.
The fungus took out "whole patches" of winter wheat stands in some
areas of Eastern Idaho, Marshall said. The worst hit fields have
suffered about 50 percent damage. Damage has shown up in both dryland
and irrigated wheat fields, but is probably worse in dryland areas
simply because those fields tend to be at higher elevations.

Washington State University [WSU] researchers have observed extensive
snow mold damage in winter wheat test plots at Almira. The damage
ranged from zero to 100 percent, depending on variety, said Stephen
Guy, WSU. "This is a fairly unusual event for that location," he
said.

[Byline: Dave Wilkins]

