[2] Tan spot - Australia: (Queensland) alert
Date: Thu 5 May 2011
Source: Queensland Country Life [edited]
http://qcl.farmonline.com.au/news/state/grains-and-cropping/general/red-alert-for-yellow-spot/2154156.aspx?storypage=0


Red alert for yellow spot
-------------------------
Western Downs consultant Vic French, Queensland, is warning growers
of the real and present danger of damaging yellow [tan] spot levels in
2011 winter cereal crops. He says wheat stubble, either standing or
displaced during the floods, is carrying visible inoculum which could
cause headaches for growers if the wet conditions continue into winter
and spring.

"The stubble is just riddled with yellow spot. If we get 2 or 3 wet
periods and moist conditions we are going to have a big problem with
the disease. We advocate a spray schedule with fungicide." Mr French
urges growers to choose yellow spot resistant or tolerant varieties
from the 2011 Grains Research and Development Corporation (GRDC) wheat
variety guide.

Greg Platz, Agri-Science Queensland, agrees there is a big danger of
cereal disease in 2011 and that proactive crop monitoring is the 1st
step in disease management. He said epidemics develop when susceptible
varieties are sown over wide areas in the presence of plentiful
inoculum under favourable environmental conditions. "Due to the wet
summer it is a given that stubbles from crops that were infected in
2010 will be very infective in 2011," he said.

