[3] Cereal cyst nematode - Australia: re-emergence (Western
Australia)
Date: Wed 4 May 2011
Source: Australian Broadcasting Corporation (ABC) Rural [edited]
http://www.abc.net.au/rural/news/content/201105/s3207175.htm


Wheat disease making a comeback
-------------------------------
A soil-borne disease that cost Australian wheat farmers over [AUD]
100 million [approx USD 107 million] in lost production 30 years ago
is making an unwelcome comeback. Cereal cyst nematode (CCN) is a
microscopic worm that lives on the roots of the wheat plant and causes
significant yield loss.

When first detected during the 1970s in South Australia and Victoria,
breeders developed new disease-resistant wheat varieties. However,
it's now been found in Western Australia for the 1st time.

Julie Nichol from CIMMYT (International Wheat and Maize Improvement
Centre) says farmers need to be educated on disease. "Farmers still
need to use those resistant cultivars in their rotational mixes." It's
not just a problem for Western Australia. All wheat farmers should be
concerned as more than 10 million hectares [about 25 million acres] of
wheat growing area is affected by CCN.

Ms Nichol [also] said that in China there are numerous species and
pathotypes of CCN whereas Australia only has one. She says work needs
to be carried out to develop resistance to these numerous pathotypes
and species to reduce the biosecurity threat to Australia.

