[Snow moulds
-----------
Snow moulds of wheat include several fungal species. Pink snow mould
is caused by _Monographella nivalis_ var. _nivalis_. It attacks plants
during wet, cool weather, but is not dependent on snow and can also
cause seedling and head blights of cereals, as well as contribute to a
number of other disease problems in co-infection with other pathogens.
Pink snow mould produces masses of microscopic spores on pink growth.
Speckled snow mould is caused by several _Typhula_ species, some of
which are restricted to areas with prolonged deep snow cover. Speckled
snow mould is grey-white and affected plants tend to bleach and
shatter easily. The speckling is due to dark sclerotia (fungal bodies)
and may or may not be present.

The snow moulds survive in dead leaves of affected plants, or as
sclerotia in soil, and generally affect a number of cereal and grass
hosts. The pathogens are most aggressive at low temperatures. Symptoms
are most apparent in early spring when the snow first melts. Plant
vigour may be markedly reduced, and in severe cases, the crowns are
killed. Surviving plants recover slowly and are sensitive to
additional stresses. Disease management includes cultural practices,
fungicide applications, and the use of host cultivars suitable to the
region which also have increased levels of resistance or tolerance to
the snow moulds.

Tan spot
--------
Tan spot (also called yellow leaf spot or blotch) is caused by the
fungus _Pyrenophora tritici-repentis_. It affects wheat but can also
attack barley, triticale, rye, and some grasses. Tan spot may cause
yield losses of up to 50 percent in favourable environments especially
under minimum tillage systems which are widely used in Australia.
Symptoms include characteristic tan leaf lesions with dark centre and
yellow surrounds which may merge to form large necrotic areas;
discolouration of glumes and seeds leading to downgrading of grain;
and short, spindly plants with reduced tillering and root development.
Plants may be fully defoliated soon after flowering. Symptoms are
generally seen later in the season in the middle and upper canopy, but
young plantlets from infected seed can show leaf spots.

The pathogen survives mainly as dormant mycelium on stubble and crop
debris. Wet conditions are necessary for spore production and
infection of growing plants resulting in rapid development of an
epidemic within a crop. Long distance spread to other crops and areas
may occur by strong winds, with infected seed or other plant material.
Disease management includes cultural measures (removal of stubble by
ploughing or burning), crop rotation, and fungicides as seed
treatments and foliar applications. Host field resistance is poorly
understood and many commercial wheat cultivars are susceptible.

Cereal cyst nematodes
---------------------
Cereal cyst nematodes (CCN) include _Heterodera avenae_ and other
species in the genus. They can cause significant yield losses on most
cereal crops when populations are high.

Roots of infested plants develop frequent branches and swellings
(cysts) leading to severe stunting and even death of the plants.
Seedlings weakened by CCNs often are invaded by soil-borne pathogens,
especially root and crown rots. Above-ground symptoms appear early in
the season as pale green patches, yellow lower leaves, and reduced
tillering. All wheat cultivars are susceptible, but some do not
support cyst formation.

The pathogens can often persist in the soil for years as cysts and
are spread by plant material, soil, and mechanical means (for example
contaminated equipment). Once they have been established in an area,
it is difficult to control or eradicate them. Disease management
requires an integrated approach including phytosanitary and cultural
measures, nematicides, crop rotation with non-cereal hosts, and the
use of partly resistant cultivars to keep populations below
economically significant thresholds. Elimination of cyst nematodes
from infected fields is usually not possible.

Different _Heterodera_ species can affect a range of crops, for
example soybean, maize, and potato.

